{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9a345d4f-992d-41fc-863f-d22e30cc851f","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to use `System.IO.Abstractions`:\n\n1. **Install the NuGet package:** `System.IO.Abstractions`\n2. **Inject `IFileSystem`** instead of calling static `File`/`Directory` methods directly:\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyService\n{\n    private readonly IFileSystem _fs;\n\n    public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;\n\n    public void Save(string path, string content)\n        => _fs.File.WriteAllText(path, content);\n\n    public string Load(string path)\n        => _fs.File.ReadAllText(path);\n\n    public bool FolderExists(string path)\n        => _fs.Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\n3. **In production**, register `new FileSystem()` (the real implementation).\n4. **In tests**, use `MockFileSystem` from `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers`:\n\n```csharp\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem();\nfs.Directory.CreateDirectory(\"/data\");\nvar svc = new MyService(fs);\n\nsvc.Save(\"/data/file.txt\", \"hello\");\nAssert.Equal(\"hello\", svc.Load(\"/data/file.txt\"));\n```\n\n**Why this over a hand-rolled interface?** `IFileSystem` covers the entire `System.IO` surface — `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, `FileInfo`, etc. — so you don't end up growing a custom abstraction every time you touch a new API.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c4011386-76ae-4757-b209-0a91fce87821","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. They have `File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, and `Directory.Exists` calls scattered across their code and want to know how to make them testable.\n\nThis is a general software engineering question — no code changes needed, just advice. Let me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":465,"requestId":"3400:F7FBE:D8C7F5:FD6472:69F4083A"},"id":"deb07ce4-d2a3-4bbf-9e4e-e73d1ac17245","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:56:22.788Z","parentId":"d59a571e-6135-45fe-a6ee-92068234b64b"}
